<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-04T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-04T21:00:00-05:00" n="1556" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1556">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/80.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to Vice Consul <persName type="to">Silliman</persName>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-04T21:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 4, 1914—9 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>We are informed three Christian Brothers, the President, Adrien
                                Astruc, Professor Adolphus Giles, both of them French, and Father
                                Vega, Mexican, were shot June 24, 4 p.m., by order of General Chao.
                                Fourteen others banished, and now at Santa Fe, New Mexico, having
                                been forced to make a payment of $5,000 ransom. By order of the same
                                General, 22 priests Zacatecas threatened death unless they paid
                                hundred thousand dollars, and upon payment they were arrested and
                                banished, and sent to El Paso.</p>
                            <p>Lay the above before General Carranza and again impress upon him the
                                seriousness of these acts and urgently insist that the parties
                                guilty be adequately punished.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>